      <!-- ── Intro ── -->
      <section class="article-section">
        <p>In a <a href="/cli-to-ai">previous deep dive</a>, I traced the arc of human-machine communication from punch cards to LLMs. The longer I sit with where we've actually landed, the more I think calling this a UX upgrade undersells it. What we're living through is a philosophical inversion of the oldest contract in computing.</p>
        <p>For sixty years, software was silent. It rendered. It waited. It obeyed &mdash; but only if you spoke its language, navigated its menus, and clicked its buttons in the right sequence. Every interface revolution from punch cards to touchscreens was the same exercise in different costume: humans accommodating machines.</p>
        <p>That contract is broken.</p>
        <p>Software can talk now. It can listen. It can reason about what you mean, not just what you typed. The page you're on talks back if you ask it to &mdash; <a href="/agent">/agent</a> is this essay's argument made operational.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- ── Table of Contents ── -->
      <nav class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
        <h2 class="toc-heading">In This Article</h2>
        <ol class="toc-list">
          <li><a href="#old-contract">The Old Contract: You Shall Learn My Language</a></li>
          <li><a href="#rupture">The Rupture: Software Learns Your Language Instead</a></li>
          <li><a href="#how-i-built">How I Made This Site Talk</a></li>
          <li><a href="#when-software-acts">Beyond the Website Agent: When Software Acts</a></li>
          <li><a href="#for-the-user">What Changes for the User</a></li>
          <li><a href="#for-the-builder">What Changes for the Builder</a></li>
          <li><a href="#risks">The Risks I Take Seriously</a></li>
